The article discusses the historic Paris Agreement on climate change, which was adopted by more than 190 countries. The agreement establishes a global framework to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and sets a goal of keeping global temperature rise below 2 degrees Celsius. It also includes provisions for countries to submit climate targets every five years and report on their progress. The agreement aims to support developing countries in pursuing clean and climate resilient growth. It sends a signal to the private sector that the global economy is moving towards clean energy and emphasizes the importance of innovation and technology in achieving climate objectives. The agreement also establishes a transparency system to ensure countries are meeting their commitments and provides confidence that existing financial commitments for climate finance will be met. The article highlights additional actions taken by the United States, including launching Mission Innovation to accelerate clean energy innovation, doubling grant-based public finance for adaptation, and commitments by states, businesses, and universities to take climate action.